Help!

  public List<Record> findList(Blueprint blueprint, Record searchRecord, int startPosition, int resultSize){
    Query<Record> query = dsCustom.find(blueprint.getRecordCollectionName(), Record.class);
    if(searchRecord != null){
      // can't use QBE as its an embedded field
      // ie. query={"map" : { "name" : "test123"}} vs. query= { "map.name" : "test123"}
      // http://www.mongodb.org/display/DOCS/Advanced+Queries#AdvancedQueries-ValueinanEmbeddedObject
      query.disableValidation();
      Record dd = (Record)searchRecord;
      for (String key : dd.keySet()) {
        query.filter(Record.MAP_FIELD + "." + key, dd.get(key));
      }
    }
    System.out.println(this.getClass().getName() + ", query=" + query);
    List<Record> resultList = new ArrayList<Record>();
    
    //now add in user credentials via AuthorizationManager
    List<ObjectId> authIdList = authorizationManager.getAuthForCurrentUser(blueprint, Authorization.READ_ONLY, Authorization.READ_WRITE);
    if(authIdList.size() > 0){
      query.filter("_id in", authIdList);  
      query.offset(startPosition);
      query.limit(resultSize);
      resultList = query.asList();
    }
    return resultList;
  } | Feedback Type: Bug Report | IP: 207.54.126.248 | Agent: Java/1.6.0_22  | URL: /about/send-feedback

Mon, 15 Aug 2011 02:24:00 -0700 | EMail: hendrik.luecke-tieke@igd.fraunhofer.de | Comments: Hi,

what about a rotated Sequence Diagram (SQ)? Instead of top-down orientation of life-lines i would prefer a left-lright orientation. Doing so would reduce the amount of empty space greatly and thus increase the data/ink-ratio (refering to Tufte) and thus increase the oversight.

In a rotated SQ, objects/classes would be aligned on the vertical axis while time is printed on the horizontal axis. (so actions to the left happen before the actions to the right happen)

Kind regards,

I've been using Architexa for a few days now and so far it's been great! Just thought I would submit a few issues, questions and suggestions. A lot of these issues are fairley trivial and nitpicky but I thought it wouldn't hurt to submit them.

Class Diagrams:
	-If you select "Image" from the palette and cancel the browse dialog then it will continue to pop up every time you mouse over the class diagram.
	-Images seem to go infront of packages and comments but behind classes. Is there any way to change the Z-Order so that pictures are behind everything?
	-If you double click an image from the open image dialog the image will not be added but the dialog will close.
	-It would be cool if I could add a general connection to a relative location on an image instead of adding them to the image as a whole. Then I could take a screenshot of a GUI and create a diagram detailing which classes are responsible for which parts of the GUI.
	-If you double click on a class to navigate to it in an editor then the cass diagram becomes dirty (requires a save)
	-Navigating to a class from a class diagram looses your cursor position in the editor.
	-The dotted line in the palette icon for General Connections is barely visible and looks solid. Also the arrow head in the General Connections icon is bigger then the arrow head for a Method Call.
	-In the class diagram the arrows for general connections usually go too far if they are pointing to a class and not far enough if they are pointing to a package. Ideally the point of the arrow would be flush with the edge of a package/class.
	-It would be nice if you could zoom in and out on a class diagram.

Sequence Diagram:
	- I get the following error message when I open a sequence diagram from the call stack, edit it, and then close it:
		An internal error occurred during: "Save Recent Diagram". java.lang.StringIndexOutOfBoundsException

Other:
	-it would be nice if this submit feedback dialog was modeless.
	-I could not find a way to remove the "Open diagram contents in a different type of diagram" icon from the toolbar. I disabled the "RSE Diagram Editors Associated Actions" Command group but the icon is still in my toolbar. I personally would prefer commands like these to be available from within the class diagram view instead of on the toolbar.
